description: From Middle English foresetten, from Old English fōresettan (“to place before, shut in, propose, prefer, precede”), equivalent to fore- +‎ set. Cognate with Dutch voorzetten (“to put in front”), German vorsetzen (“to put in front, offer, serve up”), Swedish föresätta (“to put before”).

adjectives.description: foreset (comparative more foreset, superlative most foreset)

entries.meaning: Set in fore or front part; placed ahead.
That which is set ahead or before; proposal, suggestion.
(geology) The deposition of sediment by the turbidity currents above the reservoir water level.
examples: Most deltas contain three different types of deposits: foreset, topset and bottomset beds. — Fluvial Landforms

verbs.description: foreset (third-person singular simple present foresets, present participle foresetting, simple past and past participle foreset)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To set before or in front of; bar; block; impede.
(transitive, dialectal) To ordain; assign; allot in advance.
